attributes.title: Figure 1 In Systematics, Natural History, And Hemipenial Morphology Of Dendrophidion Brunneum (Günther) (Serpentes: Colubridae), A Poorly Known Snake From The Andes Of Ecuador And Peru
attributes.description: FIGURE 1. Dendrophidion brunneum in life. Specimens are from the Río Zaña Study Site, Cajamarca Department, Peru. The contrasting head and body coloration and yellow highlights on neck scales (lower photo) are typical.

attributes.title: Figure 2 In Systematics, Natural History, And Hemipenial Morphology Of Dendrophidion Brunneum (Günther) (Serpentes: Colubridae), A Poorly Known Snake From The Andes Of Ecuador And Peru
attributes.description: FIGURE 2. Distribution of Dendrophidion brunneum. All documented localities are plotted (see Appendix). Shaded area is 1000 – 3000 m elevation; hatched area is above 3000 m.

attributes.title: Figure 4 In Systematics, Natural History, And Hemipenial Morphology Of Dendrophidion Brunneum (Günther) (Serpentes: Colubridae), A Poorly Known Snake From The Andes Of Ecuador And Peru
attributes.description: FIGURE 4. Habitat of Dendrophidion brunneum at the Río Zaña Study Site, Cajamarca Department, Peru. The photograph shows a portion of the montane humid forest from approximately 2000 – 2500 m elevation. The peak on the left, known locally as Cerro Balcón, is about 2550 m at the summit. Pale areas below the peak were patches of forest cleared for cattle and agriculture. Photograph taken in June 1987.

attributes.title: Figure 5 In Systematics, Natural History, And Hemipenial Morphology Of Dendrophidion Brunneum (Günther) (Serpentes: Colubridae), A Poorly Known Snake From The Andes Of Ecuador And Peru
attributes.description: FIGURE 5. Hemipenis of Dendrophidion brunneum (FMNH 231777) in (left to right): sulcate, asulcate, and lateral views (organ stained with alizarin red S).

attributes.title: Figure 6 In Systematics, Natural History, And Hemipenial Morphology Of Dendrophidion Brunneum (Günther) (Serpentes: Colubridae), A Poorly Known Snake From The Andes Of Ecuador And Peru
attributes.description: FIGURE 6. Details of hemipenial morphology of Dendrophidion brunneum (FMNH 231777) after staining with alizarin red. A, sulcate side at the level of the circumferential flounces. Apex of the hemipenis is toward the top; the sulcus spermaticus is on the far left (ss). The spinules appear as parallel rods embedded within the two circumferential flounces. Arrows indicate the low ridge (transverse whitish line) delimiting the distal edge of shallow irregular calyces on the right side of the sulcus spermaticus. B, A portion of the flounces from apical perspective (the flounce in the background is the proximal complete flounce) showing the regular spacing of the spinules and their lack of projecting free tips. Arrows indicate the outer edge of the proximal flounce.
